name: Bishamonten
desc: Also known as Tamonten and Vaishravana in Buddhist lore, he is the strongest of the Heavenly Kings. He protects the North and is the god of war.
strategy: Every 2 turns, Shadows will focus their Death Stare on 1 random Phantom Thief. They will prioritize attacking the Phantom Thief under the Death Stare.

name: Koumokuten
desc: Also known as Virupaksha, he is the protector of the West, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He keeps a close watch on the world with his sharp gaze.
strategy: Every 2 turns, Shadows will focus their Death Stare on 1 random Phantom Thief. They will prioritize attacking the Phantom Thief under the Death Stare.

name: Zouchouten
desc: Also known as Virudhaka, he is the protector of the South, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He is the god of the five grains, and was once the chief of the gods.
strategy: Every 2 turns, Shadows will focus their Death Stare on 1 random Phantom Thief. They will prioritize attacking the Phantom Thief under the Death Stare.

name: Jikokuten
desc: Also known as Dhritarashtra, he is the protector of the East, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He helps maintain the security of the nation.
strategy: Every 2 turns, Shadows will focus their Death Stare on 1 random Phantom Thief. They will prioritize attacking the Phantom Thief under the Death Stare.

name: Seiryu
desc: The noblest of the Ssu-Ling creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction east, the season of spring, and the element of wood. It dwells in a palace at the bottom of the ocean.
strategy:
1. At the start of battle, Seiryu gains 2 Azure Scales stacks, and gains 1 more stack every turn. Each stack decreases damage taken by 15%.
2. When Seiryu takes weakness damage, it loses 1 Azure Scales stack.
3. When Seiryu loses all Azure Scales stacks, all Phantom Thieves gain Seiryu's Might, increasing their damage.

name: Titania
desc: The queen of the fairies and Oberon's wife. She is derived from the Roman goddess Diana. She was later immortalized in Shakespeare's play "A Midsummer Night's Dream."
strategy:
1. At the end of each turn, Titania gains 2 Fairy Power stacks.
2. Titania loses 1 Fairy Power stack each time it takes a Physical attack.
3. Before the start of Titania's turn, it spends all of its Fairy Power stacks to activate Fairy Curse, decreasing all Phantom Thieves' final damage by the number of Fairy Power stacks spent Ã— 15%.

name: Vishnu
desc: One of the major Hindu gods, he is the preserver and protector of the universe. Legends claim that he will make ten appearances across time and space to strike down evil and uphold justice.
strategy:
1. At the start of battle, Vishnu summons 4 servants. Vishnu and all servants are in the Soul Link state.
Soul Link: Distributes all damage received between all Shadows who share this condition, based on the percentage of their current HP.
2. When Vishnu and its servants take skill damage, they gain Guardian's Preservation based on the attribute, and that affinity is changed to Resist. This effect lasts for 2 turns.

name: Garuda
desc: A divine bird-man in Hindu lore, he once fought the gods and received immortality in exchange for becoming Vishnu's carrier.

desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, its body is so hard that no weapons can penetrate it. It and its comrades fell into hell through holes that can still be found in modern Iga.

name: Oni
desc: An evil monster from Japanese lore known for its hideous visage and brute strength. They loot and plunder villages, massacring the townspeople with their iron clubs. They have horns on their heads, red skin, long claws, and razor-sharp teeth.

name: Oni
desc: An evil monster from Japanese lore known for its hideous visage and brute strength. They loot and plunder villages, massacring the townspeople with their iron clubs. They have horns on their heads, red skin, long claws, and razor-sharp teeth.

name: Melchizedek
desc: An angel of Gnosticism, governing over peace and righteousness. Though said to be the savior of the angels, he used to be a human, the king of Salem.
strategy:
1. Melchizedek gains 6 stacks of Divine Protection at the start of each turn.
2. Each Divine Protection stack decreases damage taken by 5%. Whenever Melchizedek takes damage from a skill or Resonance, it loses 1 stack.
3. When Melchizedek has lost all stacks of Divine Protection, all Phantom Thieves gain Divine Blessing, which increases their damage dealt.

name: Vishnu
desc: One of the major Hindu gods, he is the preserver and protector of the universe. Legends claim that he will make ten appearances across time and space to strike down evil and uphold justice.
strategy:
1. At the start of battle, Vishnu summons 4 servants. Vishnu and all servants are in the <color=#FF423F>Soul Link</color> state.
Soul Link: Distributes all damage received between all Shadows who share this condition, based on the percentage of their current HP.
2. When Vishnu and its servants take skill damage, they gain Guardian's Preservation based on the attribute, and that affinity is changed to Resist. This effect lasts for 2 turns.

name: Garuda
desc: A divine bird-man in Hindu lore, he once fought the gods and received immortality in exchange for becoming Vishnu's carrier.

name: Slime
desc: A primitive monster with a viscous body. There are various theories as to its origin, but it is still under debate. Said to compulsively collect shiny objects.

name: Quetzalcoatl
desc: An Aztec deity known as the Feathered Serpent. He created humans with his own blood and taught them how to sustain themselves.

name: Ganesha
desc: The Hindu elephant-headed god. He was originally created by Parvati in order to prevent anyone from watching her bathe. Shiva batted off his original head and replaced it with an elephant's head.

name: Jatayu
desc: The Hindu king of birds. In the Ramayana, he fought bravely against Ravana in an attempt to save Sita, Rama's wife and the seventh avatar of Vishnu, but lost.

name: Dakini
desc: Hindu deities of passion and relations. They are Kali's attendants. They eat human flesh and gather at graveyards and crematories each night. Their name means "sky dancer."

name: Dakini

name: Shiva
desc: One of the major Hindu gods, he is known as the Destroyer, but is also related to regeneration. His wife is Parvati.
strategy:
1. Shiva's skills Riot Gun and Karmic Alteration, as well as Parvati's skill Mother's Revelation, will grant Wisdom. Wisdom enhances the skill effects of Dance of Destruction and Divine Dancer's Leap.
Shiva's skill Divine Dancer's Leap and Parvati's skill Mother's Revelation will be used after the phase changes.
2. Each time Shiva takes damage of a different attribute, it loses 1 Wisdom stack (1 time for each attribute, count resets at the start of Shiva's next turn).
3. Every time a certain number of turns passes, Parvati will activate Qi Barrier, changing all of the Shadows' affinities to Null. It is removed when taking damage that is not a continuous effect.
4. The first time that Shiva or Parvati reach 1 HP, they will enter a weakened state. During this time, they cannot act and cannot be targeted. When Shiva and Parvati enter their weakened states at the same time, they will recover HP and enter the next phase.
5. When Parvati is defeated, Shiva will immediately activate Dance of Destruction, dealing damage to all Phantom Thieves.
6. When Shiva is defeated, Parvati will transform into Kali.

name: Genbu
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction north, the season of winter, and the element of water. Known to be a great warrior, it supports the Earth from below.
strategy:
Genbu has different weaknesses and resistances than normal.
After 2 turns, Genbu alternates between two skills, <color=#FF423F>High Tide</color> and <color=#FF423F>Ebb Tide</color>.
1. Ebb Tide: Inflicts the <color=#FF423F>Submerged</color> status on 2 Phantom Thieves. Clears all Shadows from the battle and summons 2 Decarabias and 2 Yurlungurs.
2. High Tide: Deals damage to all Phantom Thieves, and inflicts the Submerged status on 1 Phantom Thief.
3. Submerged: Deals damage equal to 10% of max HP at the end of each turn. Lasts 4 turns. Stackable.

name: Decarabia
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia, this demon appears as a pentacle. Keeper of jewels and herbal lore, Decarabia is said to have the ability to shape-shift at will.
strategy:
Decarabia has different weaknesses and resistances than normal.
If defeated, remove 1 <color=#FF423F>Submerged</color> stack from all Phantom Thieves. If not defeated by the time <color=#FF423F>Ebb Tide</color> begins, inflict 1 Submerged stack on all Phantom Thieves.

name: Raja Naga
desc: The king of the Naga, a half-man, half-snake tribe in Hindu lore. The dragon kings Nanda and Takshaka of Buddhist myth fall into this royal category.
strategy:
Raja Naga has different weaknesses and resistances than normal.
Raja Naga alternates between the following skills.
1. <color=#FF423F>Royal Decree</color>: Grants 3 <color=#FF423F>Royal Shield</color> stacks to all Shadows.
Royal Shield: Decreases damage taken by 15% (stacks up to 5 times). Lose 1 stack when damaged by a skill, Resonance, or Highlight.
2. <color=#FF423F>Royal Punishment</color>: Locks on to a Phantom Thief, and deals severe damage on the next turn. Remove Lock On if Raja Naga takes damage a total of 15 times from a skill, Resonance, or Highlight while locked on.
3. Other Nagas cannot be defeated while Raja Naga is on the field.

name: Unicorn
desc: A legendary white horse with a single spiral horn. It can only be tamed by a pure maiden, and its horn supposedly has miraculous healing capabilities.
strategy:
Weaknesses and resistances are different than normal.
Unicorn activates Sacred Radiance 2 turns after activating Sacred Blessing.
1. Sacred Blessing: Deals Bless damage to all Phantom Thieves. Unicorn gains 10 Purity stacks, and summons 1 Nigi Mitama.
2. Sacred Radiance: Deals heavy damage to all Phantom Thieves based on user's Purity stacks. If Unicorn has 5+ Purity stacks, also inflicts the Phantom Thieves with Rebuke.
Rebuke: Permanently increases damage taken by 50%.
Purity: Decreases Unicorn's damage taken by 5% for each stack. Lose 1 stack for each status ailment received.

name: Nigi Mitama
desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it works gently to help maintain a calm mind. It is said to aid in one's relations and sociability, and can lead one in a positive direction.
strategy:
Weaknesses and resistances are different than normal.
1. When Nigi Mitama is inflicted with a status ailment, Unicorn is inflicted with the same ailment and loses 1 stack of Purity.
2. Nigi Mitama will die after 1 action. When Nigi Mitama dies, it deals damage to Unicorn equal to Nigi Mitama's lost HP.

name: Hell Biker
desc: A motorcyclist whose violent nature turned him into a demon. His anger with himself and the world causes him to lash out, that everyone else would suffer as well.
strategy:
Hell Biker alternates between using Hellfire and Cleansing Flame.
1. Hellfire: Deal heavy Fire damage to all Phantom Thieves. Inflict Hellscorched if the target's HP is decreased by this attack. Hellscorched: Take damage equal to 35% of max HP each turn.
2. Cleansing Flame: Deal heavy Fire damage to the Phantom Thief with the highest Attack. Permanently decrease the target's Attack by 50%. Increase Hell Biker's Attack by 30%.

name: Oni
desc: An evil monster from Japanese lore known for its hideous visage and brute strength. They loot and plunder villages, massacring the townspeople with their iron clubs. They have horns on their heads, red skin, long claws, and razor-sharp teeth.
strategy:
1. Oni and Hell Biker share a Soul Link.
Soul Link: Distributes all damage received between all Shadows who share this condition, based on the percentage of their current HP.
2. Oni will target the Phantom Thief with the lowest HP.

1. Hellfire: Deal heavy Fire damage to all Phantom Thieves. Inflict Hellscorched if the target's HP is decreased by this attack. Hellscorched: Take damage equal to 35% of max HP each turn.
2. Cleansing Flame: Deal heavy Fire damage to the Phantom Thief with the highest Attack. Permanently decrease the target's Attack by 50%. Increase Hell Biker's Attack by 30%.

name: Oni
desc: An evil monster from Japanese lore known for its hideous visage and brute strength. They loot and plunder villages, massacring the townspeople with their iron clubs. They have horns on their heads, red skin, long claws, and razor-sharp teeth.
strategy:
1. Oni and Hell Biker share a Soul Link.
Soul Link: Distributes all damage received between all Shadows who share this condition, based on the percentage of their current HP.
2. Oni will target the Phantom Thief with the lowest HP.

name: Shiki-Ouji
desc: An exceptionally powerful shikigami. Only the most elite onmyoji are able to summon and bind it to paper. It can ward off disaster or cure illness, but its ordinary temperament is quite vicious.
strategy:
Weaknesses and resistances are different than normal.
1. Shiki-Ouji changes between Attack Form and Defense Form every turn.
2. In Defense Form, Shiki-Ouji gains 5 <color=#FF423F>Defensive Stance</color> stacks.
<color=#FF423F>Defensive Stance</color>: Damage taken is decreased by 10%. Lose 1 stack when taking weakness damage.
3. In Attack Form, Shiki-Ouji will act twice, and for each <color=#FF423F>Defensive Stance</color>, it will gain 1 <color=#FF423F>Offensive Stance</color> stack.
<color=#FF423F>Offensive Stance</color>: Increase Shiki-Ouji's damage dealt by 25%.
4. In Defense Form, Shiki-Ouji gains <color=#FF423F>Defense Position</color>.
Defense Position: All non-Weak attributes change to Resist for 1 turn.

name: Belphegor
desc: Demonic governor of the deadly sin of sloth. He also excels at invention and discovery. May be derived from Ba'al Pe'or, Syrian god of abundant crops.
strategy:
1. Belphegor is always Asleep. After being attacked, it will wake up, deal heavy damage to all Phantom Thieves and heal 15% of its max HP.
2. At the start of Belphegor's turn, if it is not Asleep, it will summon 2 Sandmen.
3. When Sandman is summoned, or at the start of its turn, it gains 1 Eternal Slumber stack.
4. At the start of each Phantom Thief's turn, if Belphegor is awake, Sandman will spend Eternal Slumber to put it to Sleep. This effect activates once every turn.

name: Sandman
desc: A fairy in German folklore who carries a bag of magical sand, which puts humans to sleep when thrown into their eyes. If the victim resists, the Sandman will sit on their eyelids.
strategy: When Sandman is defeated, Belphegor will go to Sleep.

name: Daisoujou
desc: A monk who died while fasting, his spiritual power allows his body to continue to exist without rotting. It is said that he will appear before people on the day of salvation.

name: Take-Minakata
desc: A Japanese god of war, hunting and fertility. He fought Take-Mikazuchi for control of Japan and lost. He escaped to Suwa, but has been prohibited to leave since then.

name: Pazuzu
desc: The Babylonian lord of wind and scorching sands. He has the body of a man, a lion's head, the claws and wings of an eagle, and has a deadly poison. The diseases he spreads can only be cured with magic.

name: Rangda
desc: A wicked witch of Balinese lore, she represents evil and is Barong's eternal rival. Even if defeated, she will come back to life, and their battle will have no end.

name: Kumbhanda
desc: A Buddhist demon said to drain human life energy. He has dark skin, stands three meters tall, and sometimes changes his shape to a gourd. Known to have once served Rudra, the god of storms.

name: Rakshasa
desc: A Hindu demon. He is an enemy of the gods and attacks humans to feed off of them. His hideous appearance strikes fear into those who see him. Rakshasa shape-shifts to deceive his enemies.

name: Kikuri-Hime
desc: The goddess of life in Shinto myth. She once mediated between Izanagi and Izanami during their confrontation in Yomi, the land of the dead.

name: Kushinada
desc: A Japanese goddess. She governs fields and fertility. All of her sisters were sacrificed to Yamata-no-Orochi, but she was saved by Susano-o and became his wife.

name: Ame-no-Uzume
desc: Japanese goddess of entertainment, she governs many sacred dances. She is most famous for luring out Amaterasu, who had barricaded herself inside a cave.

name: Barong
desc: A mystical creature in Balinese lore, it represents good and is Rangda's eternal rival. Even if defeated, it will be reborn. The result is a never-ending struggle.

name: Barong
desc: A mystical creature in Balinese lore, it represents good and is Rangda's eternal rival. Even if defeated, it will be reborn. The result is a never-ending struggle.

name: Shiisaa
desc: A holy beast said to protect houses from evil and bring good fortune. They look similar to Shinto guardian dogs, but are actually modeled after a lion. There are many stories about it in Ryukyu lore.

name: Arahabaki
desc: A mysterious god of ancient Japan. Most famously worshipped by Nagasunehiko, who was defeated in battle against Emperor Jinmu, Arahabaki came to be treated as a symbol of rebellion and defiance.

name: Belphegor
desc: Demonic governor of the deadly sin of sloth. He also excels at invention and discovery. May be derived from Ba'al Pe'or, Syrian god of abundant crops.

name: Ganesha
desc: The Hindu elephant-headed god. He was originally created by Parvati in order to prevent anyone from watching her bathe. Shiva batted off his original head and replaced it with an elephant's head.

name: Girimehkala
desc: A giant elephant monster of Sri Lankan myth, it is typically portrayed as being ridden by the Evil One, Mara. Whoever looks into its evil eye is said to be met with misfortune.

name: Seth
desc: The Egyptian god of the desert, chaos, and evil. He murdered his brother, Osiris, and tried to become chief god, but he was castrated by Osiris's son, Horus.

name: Horus
desc: An ancient god of Egypt whose eyes are the sun and moon. Revered by some as the chief god, he is often depicted as a hawk or a falcon.

name: Raja Naga
desc: The king of the Naga, a half-man, half-snake tribe in Hindu lore. The dragon kings Nanda and Takshaka of Buddhist myth fall into this royal category.

name: Quetzalcoatl
desc: An Aztec deity known as the Feathered Serpent. He created humans with his own blood and taught them how to sustain themselves.

name: Yurlungur
desc: A snake with a rainbow body from Murngin lore. He is a fertility deity who controls the weather and resides in a holy pond filled with rainbow-colored water.

name: Yurlungur
desc: A snake with a rainbow body from Murngin lore. He is a fertility deity who controls the weather and resides in a holy pond filled with rainbow-colored water.

name: Power
desc: The sixth of the nine orders of angels. It is said that they were the first order to be created. Their duty is to protect human souls from demons.

name: Principality
desc: The seventh of the nine orders of angels. They guard cities and nations, and protect various religious figures.

name: Archangel
desc: The eighth of the nine orders of angels. Their duty is to minister to humans and deliver messages. They are warriors of Heaven and lead Heaven's forces during battle with the armies of evil.

name: Angel
desc: The ninth of the nine orders of angels. They are closest in nature to humans. They watch over individuals and warn those who stray from the path.

name: Thor
desc: The Norse thunder god and son of Odin, Thor owns the power-enhancing belt Megingjard and wields Mjolnir, a hammer that causes lightning to strike and returns to its owner if thrown.

name: Okuninushi
desc: A Kunitsu deity in Japanese mythology that governs agriculture and medicine. He's said to have built the country of Izumo with Susano-o's daughter, Suseri-Hime.

name: Queen Mab
desc: The fairy queen in Celtic myth. Often identified with Titania. She would offer mead mixed with her blood to her many consorts.

name: Queen Mab
desc: The fairy queen in Celtic myth. Often identified with Titania. She would offer mead mixed with her blood to her many consorts.

name: Jatayu
desc: The Hindu king of birds. In the Ramayana, he fought bravely against Ravana in an attempt to save Sita, Rama's wife and the seventh avatar of Vishnu, but lost.

name: Garuda
desc: A divine bird-man in Hindu lore, he once fought the gods and received immortality in exchange for becoming Vishnu's carrier.

name: Clotho
desc: The youngest of the three Moirae Sisters of Greek legend. She spins the threads of life with her spindle.

name: Lachesis
desc: The middle sister of the three Moirae Sisters of Greek legend. She is the apportioner, measuring the thread which determines each person's lifespan.

name: Atropos
desc: The eldest of the three Moirae Sisters of Greek mythology. She cuts the threads of life for those whose time has come.

name: Seiryu
desc: The noblest of the Ssu-Ling creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction east, the season of spring, and the element of wood. It dwells in a palace at the bottom of the ocean.

name: Byakko
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction west, the season of autumn, and the element of metal. He is believed to be the king of all beasts.

name: Suzaku
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures in Chinese myth. It is a giant bird that is said to chirp in five beautiful voices. It represents the direction south, the season of summer, and the element of fire.

name: Genbu
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction north, the season of winter, and the element of water. Known to be a great warrior, it supports the Earth from below.

name: Moloch
desc: A Canaanite god of fire. A bronze statue of a man with a bull's head stands at his altar. The statue was heated and sacrificial children were thrown inside.

name: Yamata-no-Orochi
desc: A giant snake with eight heads that Susano-o defeated to save Kushinada-hime. The legendary sword Ame-no-Murakumo-no-Tsurugi, also known as the "Sword of Kusanagi," emerged from its belly.

name: Surt
desc: A fire giant in Norse lore. He rules the fire realm, Muspelheim, and brandishes a burning sword. At Ragnarok, he will set the world ablaze.

name: Hecatoncheires
desc: Giants born from Uranus and Gaia. The name means "those with a hundred arms." During the war of the Titans, Zeus freed them from the Underworld to help him obtain victory.

name: Melchizedek
desc: An angel of Gnosticism, governing over peace and righteousness. Though said to be the savior of the angels, he used to be a human, the king of Salem.

name: Melchizedek
desc: An angel of Gnosticism, governing over peace and righteousness. Though said to be the savior of the angels, he used to be a human, the king of Salem.

name: Nebiros
desc: The general of Hell. He keeps watch over other demons. One of Hell's greatest necromancers, he can control souls and corpses.

name: Nebiros
desc: The general of Hell. He keeps watch over other demons. One of Hell's greatest necromancers, he can control souls and corpses.

name: Oberon
desc: The king of the fairies and Titania's husband. He is quite old but, due to a curse, his looks are that of a young boy. He often flirts with human women, which sometimes earns him a scolding from his wife.

name: Titania
desc: The queen of the fairies and Oberon's wife. She is derived from the Roman goddess Diana. She was later immortalized in Shakespeare's play "A Midsummer Night's Dream."

name: Baphomet
desc: A goat-headed demon that is worshipped in Black Sabbaths. His name can be used as a catch-all term for demons in general. He would become an object of worship for witches.

name: Baphomet
desc: A goat-headed demon that is worshipped in Black Sabbaths. His name can be used as a catch-all term for demons in general. He would become an object of worship for witches.

name: Byakko
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction west, the season of autumn, and the element of metal. He is believed to be the king of all beasts.

name: Cerberus
desc: The guardian hound who prevents anyone from entering or exiting the underworld in Greek lore. It was born from Typhon and Echidna, and is the older brother of Orthrus.

name: Orthrus
desc: The two-headed pet dog belonging to the giant Geryon of Greek myth. He guarded a herd of red oxen but was killed by Hercules during one of his twelve labors.

name: Dionysus
desc: The Greek god of wine and theater. He was originally a god of life protecting the mountains of Thrace. He taught humans how to make wine.

name: Norn
desc: Goddesses of fate in Norse lore. They live below the roots of Yggdrasil and weave the threads of fate, which even the gods are bound by.

name: Norn
desc: Goddesses of fate in Norse lore. They live below the roots of Yggdrasil and weave the threads of fate, which even the gods are bound by.

name: Cu Chulainn
desc: A hero in Celtic folklore. He was called Setanta until he earned the name, "Culann's Hound." There are many tales of his adventures. He received his spear, Gae Bolg, from his mentor, Scathach.

name: Scathach
desc: A warrior woman of the Land of Shadows in Celtic lore. She taught the hero, Cu Chulainn, the art of war and gave him the spear, Gae Bolg.

name: Narcissus
desc: A young man of Greek myth. He rejected the nymph Echo, who faded to a whisper out of despair. Cursed by Nemesis, he fell in love with his own reflection and wasted away.

name: Leanan Sidhe
desc: A beautiful fairy of Irish lore that yearns for the love of a human man. She drains the life of her lovers in return for granting them artistic inspiration.

name: Kohryu
desc: Known as the Gold Dragon, it reigns over the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese lore. It is located at the center of the four beasts.

name: Beelzebub
desc: Demonic Lord of the Flies whose insect minions carry souls for him to control. He is mentioned in the Bible as a leader of evil spirits and is seen as a powerful demon.

name: Zaou-Gongen
desc: Repeller of evil found at Kinpusen by En-no-Ozunu. Believed to be a fusion of Buddha, Guanyin, and Maitreya, he's a god who originated from Japan rather than the Buddhavacana.

name: Sraosha
desc: In Zoroastrian lore, Sraosha's duty is to listen to the cry of humans for Ahura Mazda. He is also known to descend after sunset to vanquish evil. His name literally means "observance."

name: Cu Chulainn
desc: A hero in Celtic folklore. He was called Setanta until he earned the name, "Culann's Hound." There are many tales of his adventures. He received his spear, Gae Bolg, from his mentor, Scathach.

name: Scathach
desc: A warrior woman of the Land of Shadows in Celtic lore. She taught the hero, Cu Chulainn, the art of war and gave him the spear, Gae Bolg.

name: Asura
desc: The Hindu king of Asuras is named Maha Vairocana, or "One Who Shines On All." In Buddhism, he is known as Dainichi Nyorai.

name: Lakshmi
desc: The Hindu goddess of beauty and good fortune, Vishnu's wife, and Kama's mother. She is the goddess of love, believed to have been born from an ocean of milk.

name: Raphael
desc: One of the four major archangels, his name means "healer." He recites the history of the fallen angels and the creation of Adam and Eve.

name: Uriel
desc: One of the four major archangels. His name means "Flame of God," and he knows all the celestial phenomena. He is the first angel Satan met on earth.

name: King Frost
desc: The king of snow who rules over an infinite number of Jack Frosts. He has the power to freeze the entire world, but is unaware of it due to his naÃ¯ve personality.

name: Black Frost
desc: A Jack Frost that yearned for evil. This powerful demon is born when a cute Jack Frost remembers its nature as a demon.

name: Black Frost
desc: A Jack Frost that yearned for evil. This powerful demon is born when a cute Jack Frost remembers its nature as a demon.

name: Jikokuten
desc: Also known as Dhritarashtra, he is the protector of the East, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He helps maintain the security of the nation.

name: Zouchouten
desc: Also known as Virudhaka, he is the protector of the South, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He is the god of the five grains, and was once the chief of the gods.

name: Koumokuten
desc: Also known as Virupaksha, he is the protector of the West, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He keeps a close watch on the world with his sharp gaze.

name: Bishamonten
desc: Also known as Tamonten and Vaishravana in Buddhist lore, he is the strongest of the Heavenly Kings. He protects the North and is the god of war.

name: White Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a white horse with a bow in hand. A crown was granted to him, and he promises victory.

name: Black Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a black horse and carries scales. He brings famine and has the right to end lives through suffering.

name: Pale Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a pale horse and represents death. He has the power to destroy life.

name: Red Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a red horse and carries a great sword. He has the power to destroy peace and make men slay one another.

name: Dominion
desc: The fourth of the nine orders of angels. Their duty is to oversee the other angels. Their actions are the manifestation of God's will.

name: Power
desc: The sixth of the nine orders of angels. It is said that they were the first order to be created. Their duty is to protect human souls from demons.

name: Principality
desc: The seventh of the nine orders of angels. They guard cities and nations, and protect various religious figures.

name: Archangel
desc: The eighth of the nine orders of angels. Their duty is to minister to humans and deliver messages. They are warriors of Heaven and lead Heaven's forces during battle with the armies of evil.

name: Asura
desc: The Hindu king of Asuras is named Maha Vairocana, or "One Who Shines On All." In Buddhism, he is known as Dainichi Nyorai.

name: Lakshmi
desc: The Hindu goddess of beauty and good fortune, Vishnu's wife, and Kama's mother. She is the goddess of love, believed to have been born from an ocean of milk.

name: Mara
desc: A Buddhist demon that represents the fear of death. Also known as "The Evil One," he sent his daughters to tempt Buddha during his meditations.

name: Yoshitsune
desc: A Japanese general of the Genpei War near the end of the Heian era and start of the Kamakura era. His bold ingenuity and ruthless skill with a blade are still praised in Japan today.

name: Futsunushi
desc: The Nihonshoki sword deity who pacified Ashihara-no-Nakatsukuni. His name comes from "futsu," the fashion in which things are cut, and "nushi," his nature as a god.

name: Mara
desc: A Buddhist demon that represents the fear of death. Also known as "The Evil One," he sent his daughters to tempt Buddha during his meditations.

name: Shiva
desc: One of the major Hindu gods, he is known as the Destroyer, but is also related to regeneration. His wife is Parvati.

name: Vishnu
desc: One of the major Hindu gods, he is the preserver and protector of the universe. Legends claim that he will make ten appearances across time and space to strike down evil and uphold justice.

name: Beelzebub
desc: Demonic Lord of the Flies whose insect minions carry souls for him to control. He is mentioned in the Bible as a leader of evil spirits and is seen as a powerful demon.

name: Abaddon
desc: The "Destroyer" and "Angel of the Bottomless Pit" as described in ancient scriptures. He controls locusts, using them to cause massive destruction to villages.

name: Mada
desc: A giant Hindu monster. Its mouth is so enormous it can swallow the Earth and the heavens in one bite. Its name means "He Who Intoxicates."

name: Moloch
desc: A Canaanite god of fire. A bronze statue of a man with a bull's head stands at his altar. The statue was heated and sacrificial children were thrown inside.

name: Raphael
desc: One of the four major archangels, his name means "healer." He recites the history of the fallen angels and the creation of Adam and Eve.

name: Uriel
desc: One of the four major archangels. His name means "Flame of God," and he knows all the celestial phenomena. He is the first angel Satan met on earth.

name: Michael
desc: One of the four major archangels, he is at the top of the angelic hierarchy. He carries a long spear that can cut through anything, and his name means "one who is like God."

name: Gabriel
desc: One of the four major archangels. She is also the only female angel at this rank. Her name comes from the Sumerian word for "governor." She is the angel who told Mary of her pregnancy.

name: Anubis
desc: The jackal-headed god of the dead and embalming from Egyptian myth. He weighs the hearts of the dead to determine their final destination.

name: Seth
desc: The Egyptian god of the desert, chaos, and evil. He murdered his brother, Osiris, and tried to become chief god, but he was castrated by Osiris's son, Horus.

name: Thoth
desc: Egyptian moon god that takes the form of a baboon, he is the one who measures time. He gave Isis the power to resurrect Osiris after he was killed by the evil god Seth.

name: Horus
desc: An ancient god of Egypt whose eyes are the sun and moon. Revered by some as the chief god, he is often depicted as a hawk or a falcon.

name: Atavaka
desc: One of the eight Yashaou. His domain is war and protection. Once a child-eating demon, he became one of the greatest of the Wisdom Kings after the Buddha converted him to good.
strategy:
When Atavaka takes damage from a skill, it gains a Mark based on that skill's <color=#FF423F>attribute</color>, up to 7 stacks.
When it has collected 3 Marks of the same attribute, Atavaka spends all Marks to summon a Rakshasa.
When Rakshasa is defeated, it increases all Phantom Thieves' damage for that attribute. Atavaka can summon Rakshasa up to 2 times.

name: Rakshasa
desc: A Hindu demon. He is an enemy of the gods and attacks humans to feed off of them. His hideous appearance strikes fear into those who see him. Rakshasa shape-shifts to deceive his enemies.
strategy: After being defeated, all Phantom Thieves' Physical damage increases.

strategy: After being defeated, all Phantom Thieves' Curse damage increases.

name: Rakshasa
desc: A Hindu demon. He is an enemy of the gods and attacks humans to feed off of them. His hideous appearance strikes fear into those who see him. Rakshasa shape-shifts to deceive his enemies.
strategy: After being defeated, all Phantom Thieves' Almighty damage increases.

name: Kohryu
desc: Known as the Gold Dragon, it reigns over the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese lore. It is located at the center of the four beasts.
strategy:
During battle, Kohryu will summon Seiryu, Byakko, Suzaku, and Genbu.
When a Shadow is defeated, the Shadows lose that Might and it is granted to all Phantom Thieves instead.
Seiryu's Might: Grants a shield equal to 3% of max HP every turn.
Byakko's Might: Increases Attack by 20%.
Suzaku's Might: Increases damage dealt by 20%.
Genbu's Might: Increases Defense by 20%.

name: Genbu
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction north, the season of winter, and the element of water. Known to be a great warrior, it supports the Earth from below.

name: Suzaku
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It is a giant bird that is said to chirp in five beautiful voices. It represents the direction south, the season of summer, and the element of fire.

name: Byakko
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction west, the season of autumn, and the element of metal. He is believed to be the king of all beasts.

name: Seiryu
desc: The noblest of the Ssu-Ling creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction east, the season of spring, and the element of wood. It dwells in a palace at the bottom of the ocean.

name: Jikokuten
desc: Also known as Dhritarashtra, he is the protector of the East, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He helps maintain the security of the nation.
strategy:
Jikokuten has <color=#ff3b37>Blade of Sanctuary</color>.
Blade of Sanctuary: Each time damage is dealt, also grants a shield to 1 random Shadow.

name: Zouchouten
desc: Also known as Virudhaka, he is the protector of the South, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He is the god of the five grains, and was once the chief of the gods.
strategy:
Zouchouten can activate <color=#ff3b37>Growth of All Things</color>.
Growth of All Things: Randomly increases Attack, Defense, or damage of all Shadows each turn.

name: Koumokuten
desc: Also known as Virupaksha, he is the protector of the West, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He keeps a close watch on the world with his sharp gaze.
strategy:
Koumokuten can activate <color=#ff3b37>Eye of Heaven</color>.
Eye of Heaven: Select 1 Phantom Thief. Increase their damage taken, and have all Shadows focus attacks on them next turn.
After activating Eye of Heaven, Koumokuten will summon 1 Makami.

name: Bishamonten
desc: Also known as Tamonten and Vaishravana in Buddhist lore, he is the strongest of the Heavenly Kings. He protects the North and is the god of war.
strategy:
Bishamonten can activate <color=#ff3b37>Parasol of Chaos</color>.
Parasol of Chaos: Covers the Shadow with the lowest HP percentage, and changes all affinities to Resist. Lasts for 2 turns.

name: Asura
desc: The Hindu king of Asuras is named Maha Vairocana, or "One Who Shines On All." In Buddhism, he is known as Dainichi Nyorai.
strategy: Be warned, <color=#ff3b37>Asura possesses the skills of all of the Four Heavenly Kings</color>.

name: Makami
desc: A divine wolf god in Japanese folklore, also written as "Oguchi-no-Magami." It is often drawn on prayer boards to prevent fires and thefts, but it is also feared as a human-eater.
strategy: Koumokuten's loyal pet, who fights by his side.

name: Ongyo-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata. By eliminating its aura and preventing others from sensing its presence, it is able to surprise its enemies.
strategy:
1. Ongyo-Ki starts with 3 <color=#ff3b37>Damage Reduction</color> stacks, which increases the damage dealt to Phantom Thieves with elemental ailments.
2. When Fuu-Ki, Sui-Ki, or Kin-Ki are defeated, Ongyo-Ki loses 1 <color=#ff3b37>Damage Reduction</color> stack. It then gains the Domain effect from the defeated Shadow, and its affinities change.

name: Fuu-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, it sends hurricanes to blow away its enemies. Some say that Fuu-Ki is the original ninja.
strategy:
1. Fuu-Ki's <color=#81ea2c>Wind Domain</color> gives it a base chance of 80% to inflict <color=#81ea2c>Ultrawindswept</color> when attacking. Ultrawindswept lasts for 2 turns.
<color=#81ea2c>Ultrawindswept</color>: An enhanced version of Windswept inflicted by Fuu-Ki. Decreases Defense by 24%.
2. Fuu-Ki deals increased damage to Phantom Thieves in the <color=#81ea2c>Ultrawindswept</color> state.

name: Sui-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, it can cause floods with the swing of its arms. In the Taiheiki, Ki no Tomoo expelled the oni by reading a Japanese poem.
strategy:
1. Sui-Ki's <color=#00aeff>Ice Domain</color> gives it a base chance of 80% to inflict <color=#00aeff>Ultrafreeze</color> when attacking. Ultrafreeze lasts for 2 turns.
<color=#00aeff>Ultrafreeze</color>: An enhanced version of Frozen inflicted by Sui-Ki. Decreases Attack by 24%.
2. Sui-Ki deals increased damage to Phantom Thieves in the <color=#00aeff>Ultrafreeze</color> state.

name: Kin-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, its body is so hard that no weapons can penetrate it. It and its comrades fell into hell through holes that can still be found in modern Iga.
strategy:
1. Kin-Ki's <color=#ffd700>Golden Domain</color> allows it to grant <color=#ffd700>Indestructible Vajra</color> to 1 random Shadow after dealing damage.
<color=#ffd700>Indestructible Vajra</color>: Nullifies the next damage taken.
2. When Kin-Ki has <color=#ffd700>Indestructible Vajra</color>, its damage increases.

name: Daisoujou
desc: A monk who died while fasting, his spiritual power allows his body to continue to exist without rotting. It is said that he will appear before people on the day of salvation.

name: Okuninushi
desc: A Kunitsu deity in Japanese mythology that governs agriculture and medicine. He's said to have built the country of Izumo with Susano-o's daughter, Suseri-Hime.

name: Arahabaki
desc: A mysterious god of ancient Japan. Most famously worshipped by Nagasunehiko, who was defeated in battle against Emperor Jinmu, Arahabaki came to be treated as a symbol of rebellion and defiance.

name: Belphegor
desc: Demonic governor of the deadly sin of sloth. He also excels at invention and discovery. May be derived from Ba'al Pe'or, Syrian god of abundant crops.

name: Pazuzu
desc: The Babylonian lord of wind and scorching sands. He has the body of a man, a lion's head, the claws and wings of an eagle, and has a deadly poison. The diseases he spreads can only be cured with magic.

name: Rangda
desc: A wicked witch of Balinese lore, she represents evil and is Barong's eternal rival. Even if defeated, she will come back to life, and their battle will have no end.

name: Kumbhanda
desc: A Buddhist demon said to drain human life energy. He has dark skin, stands three meters tall, and sometimes changes his shape to a gourd. Known to have once served Rudra, the god of storms.

name: Rakshasa
desc: A Hindu demon. He is an enemy of the gods and attacks humans to feed off of them. His hideous appearance strikes fear into those who see him. Rakshasa shape-shifts to deceive his enemies.

name: Ganesha
desc: The Hindu elephant-headed god. He was originally created by Parvati in order to prevent anyone from watching her bathe. Shiva batted off his original head and replaced it with an elephant's head.

name: Girimehkala
desc: A giant elephant monster of Sri Lankan myth, it is typically portrayed as being ridden by the Evil One, Mara. Whoever looks into its evil eye is said to be met with misfortune.

name: Seth
desc: The Egyptian god of the desert, chaos, and evil. He murdered his brother, Osiris, and tried to become chief god, but he was castrated by Osiris's son, Horus.

name: Horus
desc: An ancient god of Egypt whose eyes are the sun and moon. Revered by some as the chief god, he is often depicted as a hawk or a falcon.

name: Kikuri-Hime
desc: The goddess of life in Shinto myth. She once mediated between Izanagi and Izanami during their confrontation in Yomi, the land of the dead.

name: Kushinada
desc: A Japanese goddess. She governs fields and fertility. All of her sisters were sacrificed to Yamata-no-Orochi, but she was saved by Susano-o and became his wife.

name: Ame-no-Uzume
desc: Japanese goddess of entertainment, she governs many sacred dances. She is most famous for luring out Amaterasu, who had barricaded herself inside a cave.

name: Barong
desc: A mystical creature in Balinese lore, it represents good and is Rangda's eternal rival. Even if defeated, it will be reborn. The result is a never-ending struggle.

name: Barong
desc: A mystical creature in Balinese lore, it represents good and is Rangda's eternal rival. Even if defeated, it will be reborn. The result is a never-ending struggle.

name: Shiisaa
desc: A holy beast said to protect houses from evil and bring good fortune. They look similar to Shinto guardian dogs, but are actually modeled after a lion. There are many stories about it in Ryukyu lore.

name: Shiisaa

name: Raja Naga
desc: The king of the Naga, a half-man, half-snake tribe in Hindu lore. The dragon kings Nanda and Takshaka of Buddhist myth fall into this royal category.

name: Quetzalcoatl
desc: An Aztec deity known as the Feathered Serpent. He created humans with his own blood and taught them how to sustain themselves.

name: Yurlungur
desc: A snake with a rainbow body from Murngin lore. He is a fertility deity who controls the weather and resides in a holy pond filled with rainbow-colored water.

desc: The seventh of the nine orders of angels. They guard cities and nations, and protect various religious figures.

desc: The eighth of the nine orders of angels. Their duty is to minister to humans and deliver messages. They are warriors of Heaven and lead Heaven's forces during battle with the armies of evil.

name: Angel
desc: The ninth of the nine orders of angels. They are closest in nature to humans. They watch over individuals and warn those who stray from the path.

name: Kin-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, its body is so hard that no weapons can penetrate it. It and its comrades fell into hell through holes that can still be found in modern Iga.
strategy:
1. Kin-Ki's <color=#ffd700>Golden Domain</color> allows it to grant <color=#ffd700>Indestructible Vajra</color> to 1 random Shadow after dealing damage.
<color=#ffd700>Indestructible Vajra</color>: Nullifies the next damage taken.
2. When Kin-Ki has <color=#ffd700>Indestructible Vajra</color>, its damage increases.

name: Fuu-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, it sends hurricanes to blow away its enemies. Some say that Fuu-Ki is the original ninja.
strategy:
1. Fuu-Ki's <color=#81ea2c>Wind Domain</color> gives it a base chance of 80% to inflict <color=#81ea2c>Ultrawindswept</color> when attacking. Ultrawindswept lasts for 2 turns.
<color=#81ea2c>Ultrawindswept</color>: An enhanced version of Windswept inflicted by Fuu-Ki. Decreases Defense by 24%.
2. Fuu-Ki deals increased damage to Phantom Thieves in the <color=#81ea2c>Ultrawindswept</color> state.

name: Ongyo-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata. By eliminating its aura and preventing others from sensing its presence, it is able to surprise its enemies.
strategy:
1. Ongyo-Ki starts with 3 <color=#ff3b37>Damage Reduction</color> stacks, which increases the damage dealt to Phantom Thieves with elemental ailments.
2. When Fuu-Ki, Sui-Ki, or Kin-Ki are defeated, Ongyo-Ki loses 1 <color=#ff3b37>Damage Reduction</color> stack. It then gains the Domain effect from the defeated Shadow, and its affinities change.

name: Shadow Kiuchi
desc: Takeyuki Kiuchi's form in the cognitive world. His appearance reflects his distorted desires.

name: Cupid Kiuchi
desc: Shadow Kiuchi completely distorted by desire. Having lost all sense of self, he can no longer maintain a human form.

name: Cupid Cheerleader 1
desc: Kiuchi's personal cheerleader born from his cognition. She exists solely to cheer him on.

name: Cupid Cheerleader 2
desc: Kiuchi's personal cheerleader born from his cognition. She exists solely to cheer him on.

name: Jack-o'-Lantern
desc: A drunkard who tricked the Devil out of taking him to Hell. When refused entry to Heaven, he was forced to wander the earth with only an ember as a light.

name: Jack-o'-Lantern

name: Bicorn
desc: An evil creature with two curving horns from European folklore. It represents impurity, unlike the Unicorn. Said to be derived from Re'em in the Bible. Another legend says that it feeds off of loyal husbands.

name: Agathion
desc: A general term for familiars used by Judeo-Christian magicians, they are usually sealed away in bottles, rings, or talismans. They torment the target selected by the conjuror.

name: Agathion
desc: A general term for familiars used by Judeo-Christian magicians, they are usually sealed away in bottles, rings, or talismans. They torment the target selected by the conjuror.

name: Succubus
desc: A female demon of European lore in medieval times. They visit sleeping men and have sexual intercourse with them. The victims don't wake up but may dream of the encounter.

name: Jack-o'-Lantern

name: Mokoi
desc: Evil spirits of Murngin lore believed to be reborn shadows. They kidnap and eat children, and strike down any sorcerer who uses black magic.

name: Jack-o'-Lantern
desc: A drunkard who tricked the Devil out of taking him to Hell. When refused entry to Heaven, he was forced to wander the earth with only an ember as a light.

name: Eligor
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. He looks like a knight and has the power to see things to come. He also knows much about war.

name: Moloch
desc: A Canaanite god of fire. A bronze statue of a man with a bull's head stands at his altar. The statue was heated and sacrificial children were thrown inside.

name: Moloch
desc: A Canaanite god of fire. A bronze statue of a man with a bull's head stands at his altar. The statue was heated and sacrificial children were thrown inside.

name: Jack Frost
desc: A winter fairy of European descent. He leaves ice patterns on windows and nips people's noses. Though normally an innocent creature, he will freeze his victims to death if provoked.

name: Thor
desc: The Norse thunder god and son of Odin, Thor owns the power-enhancing belt Megingjard and wields Mjolnir, a hammer that causes lightning to strike and returns to its owner if thrown.

name: Agathion
desc: A general term for familiars used by Judeo-Christian magicians, they are usually sealed away in bottles, rings, or talismans. They torment the target selected by the conjuror.

name: Bicorn
desc: An evil creature with two curving horns from European folklore. It represents impurity, unlike the Unicorn. Said to be derived from Re'em in the Bible. Another legend says that it feeds off of loyal husbands.

name: Titania
desc: The queen of the fairies and Oberon's wife. She is derived from the Roman goddess Diana. She was later immortalized in Shakespeare's play "A Midsummer Night's Dream."

name: Isis
desc: Osiris's wife as well as his younger sister. Upon the death of her husband, she revived him with her incredible magic power. Isis is seen at many gravesites as the guardian goddess of the dead.

name: Lamia
desc: A half-human, half-snake female monster of Greek myth, she was once the queen of Libya. Zeus's jealous wife, Hera, killed her children, causing her to go mad and transform into a monster.

name: Oberon
desc: The king of the fairies and Titania's husband. He is quite old but, due to a curse, his looks are that of a young boy. He often flirts with human women, which sometimes earns him a scolding from his wife.

name: Succubus
desc: A female demon of European lore in medieval times. They visit sleeping men and have sexual intercourse with them. The victims don't wake up but may dream of the encounter.

name: Cu Chulainn
desc: A hero in Celtic folklore. He was called Setanta until he earned the name, "Culann's Hound." There are many tales of his adventures. He received his spear, Gae Bolg, from his mentor, Scathach.

name: Dominion
desc: The fourth of the nine orders of angels. Their duty is to oversee the other angels. Their actions are the manifestation of God's will.

name: Gabriel
desc: One of the four major archangels. She is also the only female angel at this rank. Her name comes from the Sumerian word for "governor." She is the angel who told Mary of her pregnancy.

name: Black Frost
desc: A Jack Frost that yearned for evil. This powerful demon is born when a cute Jack Frost remembers its demonic nature.

name: King Frost
desc: The king of snow who rules over an infinite number of Jack Frosts. He has the power to freeze the entire world, but is unaware of it due to his naÃ¯ve personality.

name: Michael
desc: One of the four major archangels, he is at the top of the angelic hierarchy. He carries a long spear that can cut through anything, and his name means "one who is like God."

name: Mokoi
desc: Evil spirits of Murngin lore believed to be reborn shadows. They kidnap and eat children, and strike down any sorcerer who uses black magic.

name: Oni
desc: An evil monster from Japanese lore known for its hideous visage and brute strength. They loot and plunder villages, massacring the townspeople with their iron clubs. They have horns on their heads, red skin, long claws, and razor-sharp teeth.

name: Orthrus
desc: The two-headed pet dog belonging to the giant Geryon of Greek myth. He guarded a herd of red oxen but was killed by Hercules during one of his twelve labors.

name: Parvati
desc: A beautiful Hindu goddess of love and one of Shiva's wives. Always by his side, she played a role in opening his third eye. She can turn into Durga or Kali when angered.

name: Rangda
desc: A wicked witch of Balinese lore, she represents evil and is Barong's eternal rival. Even if defeated, she will come back to life, and their battle will have no end.

name: Lilim
desc: A demon who tempts sleeping men and attacks infants. She is the daughter of the demoness, Lilith. Like her mother, she drains men of their essence.

name: Sandalphon
desc: Metatron's twin brother in Judeo-Christian lore, he is the master of heavenly songs. It is said that a human would take 500 years to walk the length of his body.

name: Sarasvati
desc: The Hindu goddess of rivers, and patron of speech, writing, learning, the arts, and sciences. Brahma is her husband.

name: Unicorn
desc: A legendary white horse with a single spiral horn. It can only be tamed by a pure maiden, and its horn supposedly has miraculous healing capabilities.

name: Yoshitsune
desc: A Japanese general of the Genpei War near the end of the Heian era and start of the Kamakura era. His bold ingenuity and ruthless skill with a blade are still praised in Japan today.

name: Kurama Tengu
desc: A type of tengu said to have lived on Mt. Kurama in Kyoto. The most powerful and well-known of the tengu, they have the power to fend off disease and bring good fortune.

name: Jatayu
desc: The Hindu king of birds. In the Ramayana, he fought bravely against Ravana in an attempt to save Sita, Rama's wife and the seventh avatar of Vishnu, but lost.

name: Archangel
desc: The eighth of the nine orders of angels. Their duty is to minister to humans and deliver messages. They are warriors of Heaven and lead Heaven's forces during battle with the armies of evil.

name: Suzaku
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It is a giant bird that is said to chirp in five beautiful voices. It represents the direction south, the season of summer, and the element of fire.

name: Clotho
desc: The youngest of the three Moirae Sisters of Greek legend. She spins the threads of life with her spindle.

name: Neko Shogun
desc: A prophetic Taoist god, originally known as Mao Shogun. Due to a linguistic error involving the Chinese word for "cat," his name was changed to Neko Shogun.

name: Anubis
desc: The jackal-headed god of the dead and embalming from Egyptian myth. He weighs the hearts of the dead to determine their final destination.

name: Pazuzu
desc: The Babylonian lord of wind and scorching sands. He has the body of a man, a lion's head, the claws and wings of an eagle, and has a deadly poison. The diseases he spreads can only be cured with magic.

name: Okuninushi
desc: A Kunitsu deity in Japanese mythology that governs agriculture and medicine. He's said to have built the country of Izumo with Susano-o's daughter, Suseri-Hime.

name: Byakko
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction west, the season of autumn, and the element of metal. He is believed to be the king of all beasts.

name: Horus
desc: An ancient god of Egypt whose eyes are the sun and moon. Revered by some as the chief god, he is often depicted as a hawk or a falcon.

name: Lakshmi
desc: The Hindu goddess of beauty and good fortune, Vishnu's wife, and Kama's mother. She is the goddess of love, believed to have been born from an ocean of milk.

name: Kohryu
desc: Known as the Gold Dragon, it reigns over the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese lore. It is located at the center of the four beasts.

name: Regent
desc: A bluish-tinged diamond that Napoleon Bonaparte had mounted to the pommel of his sword. It was named after the French Regent Philippe II, Duke of Orleans, who had purchased it in 1717.

name: Queen's Necklace
desc: The diamond necklace that Jeanne de la Motte swindled from jewelers in 1785 by claiming it was on behalf of the Queen of France, Marie Antoinette.

name: Inugami
desc: A dog spirit said to possess people in Japanese lore. Those possessed are in a state of "inu-tsuki" and lose consciousness. Onmyoji use Inugami as familiars.

name: Pixie
desc: Friendly fairies of the forest that tend to hide from humans. They like to play tricks on lazy people. It is said they are the souls of dead, unbaptized children.

name: Incubus
desc: A male demon of European lore in medieval times. They visit sleeping women and have sexual intercourse with them. The resulting children become witches or wizards.

name: Nue
desc: A creature of Japanese lore with a monkey's head, tiger's legs, and snake's tail. The Tale of Heike says it hid behind a dark cloud each night to attack the Emperor.

name: Angel
desc: The ninth of the nine orders of angels. They are closest in nature to humans. They watch over individuals and warn those who stray from the path.

name: Koppa Tengu
desc: A type of tengu. Their spiritual power is weaker than other tengu, so they are much smaller. They are said to be the reincarnations of long-lived wolves.

name: Orobas
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. Known as the Prince of Hell, he appears as a horse and answers questions of the past, present, and future. He is faithful to his conjurer.

name: Nekomata
desc: Long-lived cats are said to become these malevolent cat demons. Their powers vary according to how long they have lived, ranging from shape-shifting to controlling the dead.

name: Leanan Sidhe
desc: A beautiful fairy of Irish lore that yearns for the love of a human man. She drains the life of her lovers in return for granting them artistic inspiration.

name: Hua Po
desc: A spirit of Chinese folklore who dwells in trees once used for hangings. She is smaller than a human and cannot speak, but her voice is said to be as clear and as beautiful as a bird's song.

name: Ippon-Datara
desc: A one-eyed, one-legged monster said to live deep in the mountains of Kumano, Japan. It's believed to be the degraded blacksmith god, Ame no Me-Hitotsu no Kami.

name: Mandrake
desc: A magical plant whose roots look like a human. They are valued for their healing properties in potions, but the screams they let out when pulled from the ground will kill anyone who hears them.

name: Silky
desc: A fairy of England and Scotland. She carries out household chores while everyone sleeps and is a welcome spirit. It is said you can hear her silk skirt rustle as she works.

name: Sudama
desc: A spirit of rivers and mountains in Japanese lore, it dwells in ancient trees and ageless rocks. They are not evil, and will often appear as humans or supernatural wonders to warn people.

name: Obariyon
desc: A "piggyback monster" of Japan that jumps on the backs of those who pass grassy paths. It is heavy and not easily removed, but will turn into gold coins if you can carry it back home.

name: Bugs
desc: A Welsh creature commonly known as "Bugbear" or the "Boogeyman." Its existence is often used by mothers to scare children into behaving.

name: Seth
desc: The Egyptian god of the desert, chaos, and evil. He murdered his brother, Osiris, and tried to become chief god, but he was castrated by Osiris's son, Horus.

name: Vishnu
desc: One of the major Hindu gods, he is the preserver and protector of the universe. Legends claim that he will make ten appearances across time and space to strike down evil and uphold justice.

name: Mothman
desc: A cryptid sighted during the 60sâ€“80s in West Virginia. It has shining red eyes and is named for the fin-like appendages on its sides. It uses its keen sense for blood to track down the source and feed on it.

name: Onmoraki
desc: A monstrous, fire spitting, Japanese bird with a man's face. It is actually a corpse that was not given a proper memorial service. They appear before monks who neglect their duties.

name: Makami
desc: A divine wolf god in Japanese folklore, also written as "Oguchi-no-Magami." It is often drawn on prayer boards to prevent fires and thefts, but it is also feared as a human-eater.

name: Decarabia
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia, this demon appears as a pentacle. Keeper of jewels and herbal lore, Decarabia is said to have the ability to shape-shift at will.

name: Koropokguru
desc: Small human-like creatures that have kind, calm personalities. Once coexisting with the Ainu people of Japan, there was a falling out at some point, and they disappeared.

name: Ganesha
desc: The Hindu elephant-headed god. He was originally created by Parvati in order to prevent anyone from watching her bathe. Shiva batted off his original head and replaced it with an elephant's head.

name: Lachesis
desc: The middle sister of the three Moirae Sisters of Greek legend. She is the apportioner, measuring the thread which determines each person's lifespan.

name: Shiki-Ouji
desc: An exceptionally powerful shikigami. Only the most elite onmyoji are able to summon and bind it to paper. It can ward off disaster or cure illness, but its ordinary temperament is quite vicious.

name: Kin-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, its body is so hard that no weapons can penetrate it. It and its comrades fell into hell through holes that can still be found in modern Iga.

name: Cerberus
desc: The guardian hound who prevents anyone from entering or exiting the underworld in Greek lore. It was born from Typhon and Echidna, and is the older brother of Orthrus.

name: Ame-no-Uzume
desc: Japanese goddess of entertainment, she governs many sacred dances. She is most famous for luring out Amaterasu, who had barricaded herself inside a cave.

name: Phoenix
desc: The legendary bird of Chinese myth, said to appear only in times of peace. It is the ruler of all birds. When it dies, birds across the land chirp with sadness.

name: Jikokuten
desc: Also known as Dhritarashtra, he is the protector of the East, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He helps maintain the security of the nation.

name: Zouchouten
desc: Also known as Virudhaka, he is the protector of the South, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He is the god of the five grains, and was once the chief of the gods.

name: Arahabaki
desc: A mysterious god of ancient Japan. Most famously worshipped by Nagasunehiko, who was defeated in battle against Emperor Jinmu, Arahabaki came to be treated as a symbol of rebellion and defiance.

name: Arahabaki
desc: A mysterious god of ancient Japan. Most famously worshipped by Nagasunehiko, who was defeated in battle against Emperor Jinmu, Arahabaki came to be treated as a symbol of rebellion and defiance.

name: Belphegor
desc: Demonic governor of the deadly sin of sloth. He also excels at invention and discovery. May be derived from Ba'al Pe'or, Syrian god of abundant crops.

name: High Pixie
desc: The leader of a swarm of pixies. Any pixie in a leadership role or with remarkable power is called by this name.

name: Hell Biker
desc: A motorcyclist whose violent nature turned him into a demon. His anger with himself and the world causes him to lash out, that everyone else would suffer as well.

name: Yamata-no-Orochi
desc: A giant snake with eight heads that Susano-o defeated to save Kushinada-hime. The legendary sword Ame-no-Murakumo-no-Tsurugi, also known as the "Sword of Kusanagi," emerged from its belly.

name: Norn
desc: Goddesses of fate in Norse lore. They live below the roots of Yggdrasil and weave the threads of fate, which even the gods are bound by.

name: Mada
desc: A giant Hindu monster. Its mouth is so enormous it can swallow the Earth and the heavens in one bite. Its name means "He Who Intoxicates."

name: Genbu
desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction north, the season of winter, and the element of water. Known to be a great warrior, it supports the Earth from below.

name: Slime
desc: A primitive monster with a viscous body. There are various theories as to its origin, but it is still under debate. Said to compulsively collect shiny objects.

name: Apsaras
desc: Hindu water spirits, they are beautiful young women who dance for the gods. They also guide heroes fallen in battle to paradise.

name: Kodama
desc: Japanese plant spirits born from trees that have lived for a hundred years. Cutting down one of these trees is said to cause misfortune.

name: Kushi Mitama
desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it uses its power to bring blessings related to healing illnesses and staying healthy. It is said to have supernatural powers and cause mysterious events.

name: Nigi Mitama
desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it works gently to help maintain a calm mind. It is said to aid in one's relations and sociability, and can lead one in a positive direction.

name: Rakshasa
desc: A Hindu demon. He is an enemy of the gods and attacks humans to feed off of them. His hideous appearance strikes fear into those who see him. Rakshasa shape-shifts to deceive his enemies.

name: Sandman
desc: A fairy in German folklore who carries a bag of magical sand, which puts humans to sleep when thrown into their eyes. If the victim resists, the Sandman will sit on their eyelids.

name: Anzu
desc: An evil deity of Mesopotamian folklore with an eagle's body and lion's head. While the god Enlil purified himself, Anzu stole the Tablets of Destiny from him.

name: Black Ooze
desc: A mass of malevolent intent and emotion that failed to become a true demon. All it does is eat, prey, and grow.

name: Mitra
desc: An ancient Persian god of contracts. He was also revered as a harvest-bringing sun god when he was introduced to the Zoroastrian religion.

name: Atropos
desc: The eldest of the three Moirae Sisters of Greek mythology. She cuts the threads of life for those whose time has come.

name: Kikuri-Hime
desc: The goddess of life in Shinto myth. She once mediated between Izanagi and Izanami during their confrontation in Yomi, the land of the dead.

name: Koumokuten
desc: Also known as Virupaksha, he is the protector of the West, and is one of the four Heavenly Kings of Buddhist origin. He keeps a close watch on the world with his sharp gaze.

name: Yatagarasu
desc: A divine creature in Japanese lore. They are three-legged birds sent by Amaterasu to help humans. They are said to have helped Emperor Jinmu claim victory.

name: Nebiros
desc: The general of Hell. He keeps watch over other demons. One of Hell's greatest necromancers, he can control souls and corpses.

name: Seiryu
desc: The noblest of the Ssu-Ling creatures of Chinese myth. It represents the direction east, the season of spring, and the element of wood. It dwells in a palace at the bottom of the ocean.

name: Bishamonten
desc: Also known as Tamonten and Vaishravana in Buddhist lore, he is the strongest of the Heavenly Kings. He protects the North and is the god of war.

name: Futsunushi
desc: The Nihonshoki sword deity who pacified Ashihara-no-Nakatsukuni. His name comes from "futsu," the fashion in which things are cut, and "nushi," his nature as a god.

name: Asura
desc: The Hindu king of Asuras is named Maha Vairocana, or "One Who Shines On All." In Buddhism, he is known as Dainichi Nyorai.

name: Raphael
desc: One of the four major archangels, his name means "healer." He recites the history of the fallen angels and the creation of Adam and Eve.

name: Zaou-Gongen
desc: Repeller of evil found at Kinpusen by En-no-Ozunu. Believed to be a fusion of Buddha, Guanyin, and Maitreya, he's a god who originated from Japan rather than the Buddhavacana.

name: Sraosha
desc: In Zoroastrian lore, Sraosha's duty is to listen to the cry of humans for Ahura Mazda. He is also known to descend after sunset to vanquish evil. His name literally means "observance."

name: Uriel
desc: One of the four major archangels. His name means "Flame of God," and he knows all the celestial phenomena. He is the first angel Satan met on earth.

name: Saki Mitama
desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it brings great bounty from the hunt. It is said to aid in love, profit, and growth, and can create new paths.

name: Berith
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. Known as the Duke of Hell, he rides a gigantic horse and burns those without manners.

name: Shiisaa
desc: A holy beast said to protect houses from evil and bring good fortune. They look similar to Shinto guardian dogs, but are actually modeled after a lion. There are many stories about it in Ryukyu lore.

name: Yaksini
desc: A female demon in Hindu lore. Though originally a Dravidian fertility goddess, the spread of Hinduism changed perception of her to a demonic figure. Usually depicted as a nude, voluptuous female.

name: Naga
desc: Half-snake, half-human divine beings in Hindu lore, worshipped as bringers of rain. They live in the bottoms of lakes and seas, singing and dancing when they are not fighting.

name: Sui-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, it can cause floods with the swing of its arms. In the Taiheiki, Ki no Tomoo expelled the oni by reading a Japanese poem.

name: Flauros
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. He appears as a leopard and can see the past and future. He can control fire and burn all his adversaries to death.

name: Setanta
desc: A brave young man in Celtic myth. After defeating a fierce guard dog, he volunteered to take its place, earning him the nickname "Hound of Culann."

name: Take-Minakata
desc: A Japanese god of war, hunting and fertility. He fought Take-Mikazuchi for control of Japan and lost. He escaped to Suwa, but has been prohibited to leave since then.

name: Principality
desc: The seventh of the nine orders of angels. They guard cities and nations, and protect various religious figures.

name: Ara Mitama
desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it has the power to grant ferocity. It is said to aid in one's bravery, growth, and endeavors, though it can lead in a negative direction.

name: Thoth
desc: Egyptian moon god that takes the form of a baboon, he is the one who measures time. He gave Isis the power to resurrect Osiris after he was killed by the evil god Seth.

name: Kaiwan
desc: A god in Assyrian legend, his name is interchangeable with Sakkut, another incarnation of the star-god, Saturn.

name: Mithras
desc: A sun deity who was worshipped in the Roman Empire from the 1st to the 4th century AD. He was said to be reborn after death, and a festival was held on the winter solstice for him.

name: Hariti
desc: Also known as Kishimojin, she once ate children, but stopped after Buddha changed her ways. She now eats pomegranates and is a goddess of parenting.

name: Matador
desc: A master sportsman who entertains the audience in exchange for his own life: one mistake can mean death. Some believe that matadors who die while performing remain in this world.

name: Kumbhanda
desc: A Buddhist demon said to drain human life energy. He has dark skin, stands three meters tall, and sometimes changes his shape to a gourd. Known to have once served Rudra, the god of storms.

name: Kelpie
desc: A horse-like fairy of Celtic folklore that lives by the water. It drowns those who ride on it, but is a valuable mount if you can tame it.

name: Andras
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. The great Marquis of Hell, he appears where there is battle to stoke the hatred within soldiers. He helps defeat the enemies of those who summon him.

name: White Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a white horse with a bow in hand. A crown was granted to him, and he promises victory.

name: Queen Mab
desc: The fairy queen in Celtic myth. Often identified with Titania. She would offer mead mixed with her blood to her many consorts.

name: Narcissus
desc: A young man of Greek myth. He rejected the nymph Echo, who faded to a whisper out of despair. Cursed by Nemesis, he fell in love with his own reflection and wasted away.

name: Trumpeter
desc: Angels that sound the trumpets at the time of the apocalypse. As each trumpet sounds, the more plagues and disasters will occur, turning the earth into a land of death and suffering.

name: Lilith
desc: Said to have been Adam's first wife, she desired to be his equal and refused to obey him. She was cast out of Eden and became a demon of the night. She is the mother of the demoness, Lilim.

name: Kali
desc: A goddess of death and destruction. She is said to be another face of Parvati. She is violent, wears a string of skulls, and carries bloody weapons, but she also blesses her followers.

name: Beelzebub
desc: Demonic Lord of the Flies whose insect minions carry souls for him to control. He is mentioned in the Bible as a leader of evil spirits and is seen as a powerful demon.

name: Power
desc: The sixth of the nine orders of angels. It is said that they were the first order to be created. Their duty is to protect human souls from demons.

name: Hecatoncheires
desc: Giants born from Uranus and Gaia. The name means "those with a hundred arms." During the war of the Titans, Zeus freed them from the Underworld to help him obtain victory.

name: Yurlungur
desc: A snake with a rainbow body from Murngin lore. He is a fertility deity who controls the weather and resides in a holy pond filled with rainbow-colored water.

name: Girimehkala
desc: A giant elephant monster of Sri Lankan myth, it is typically portrayed as being ridden by the Evil One, Mara. Whoever looks into its evil eye is said to be met with misfortune.

name: Mara
desc: A Buddhist demon that represents the fear of death. Also known as "The Evil One," he sent his daughters to tempt Buddha during his meditations.

name: Fuu-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata, it sends hurricanes to blow away its enemies. Some say that Fuu-ki is the original ninja.

name: Ongyo-Ki
desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata. By eliminating its aura and preventing others from sensing its presence, it is able to surprise its enemies.

name: Abaddon
desc: The "Destroyer" and "Angel of the Bottomless Pit" as described in ancient scriptures. He controls locusts, using them to cause massive destruction to villages.

name: Quetzalcoatl
desc: An Aztec deity known as the Feathered Serpent. He created humans with his own blood and taught them how to sustain themselves.

name: Surt
desc: A fire giant in Norse lore. He rules the fire realm, Muspelheim, and brandishes a burning sword. At Ragnarok, he will set the world ablaze.

name: Baphomet
desc: A goat-headed demon that is worshipped in Black Sabbaths. His name can be used as a catch-all term for demons in general. He would become an object of worship for witches.

name: Raja Naga
desc: The king of the Naga, a half-man, half-snake tribe in Hindu lore. The dragon kings Nanda and Takshaka of Buddhist myth fall into this royal category.

name: Barong
desc: A mystical creature in Balinese lore, it represents good and is Rangda's eternal rival. Even if defeated, it will be reborn. The result is a never-ending struggle.

name: Garuda
desc: A divine bird-man in Hindu lore, he once fought the gods and received immortality in exchange for becoming Vishnu's carrier.

name: Daisoujou
desc: A monk who died while fasting, his spiritual power allows his body to continue to exist without rotting. It is said that he will appear before people on the day of salvation.

name: Ose
desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia, he is known as the President of Hell. He can shape-shift from leopard to human and reveal the truth behind divine mysteries.

name: Kushinada
desc: A Japanese goddess. She governs fields and fertility. All of her sisters were sacrificed to Yamata-no-Orochi, but she was saved by Susano-o and became his wife.

name: Dakini
desc: Hindu deities of passion and relations. They are Kali's attendants. They eat human flesh and gather at graveyards and crematories each night. Their name means "sky dancer."

name: Pale Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a pale horse and represents death. He has the power to destroy life.

name: Black Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a black horse and carries scales. He brings famine and has the right to end lives through suffering.

name: Red Rider
desc: One of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a red horse and carries a great sword. He has the power to destroy peace and make men slay one another.

name: Scathach
desc: A warrior woman of the Land of Shadows in Celtic lore. She taught the hero, Cu Chulainn, the art of war and gave him the spear, Gae Bolg.

name: Valkyrie
desc: "Choosers of the slain" in Norse lore. Armed with shining armor and swords, they look for brave warriors to take to Valhalla, so that they may fight in Ragnarok.

name: Dionysus
desc: The Greek god of wine and theater. He was originally a god of life protecting the mountains of Thrace. He taught humans how to make wine.

name: Melchizedek
desc: An angel of Gnosticism, governing over peace and righteousness. Though said to be the savior of the angels, he used to be a human, the king of Salem.

name: Jack-o'-Lantern
desc: A drunkard who tricked the Devil out of taking him to Hell. When refused entry to Heaven, he was forced to wander the earth with only an ember as a light.
